==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mort
<hw>Mort</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Icel.
<ets>margt</ets>, neut. of <ets>margr</ets> many.]</ety> <def>A great
quantity or number.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was a <qex>mort</qex> of merrymaking.</q>
<rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mort
<hw>Mort</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etym. uncert.]</ety> <def>A woman; a
female.</def> <mark>[Cant, archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Male gypsies all, not a <qex>mort</qex> among them.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mort
<hw>Mort</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A salmon in its third year.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mort
<hw>Mort</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., death, fr. L. <ets>mors</ets>,
<ets>mortis</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Death; esp., the death of
game in the chase.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A note or series of notes sounded on a horn at the
death of game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sportsman then sounded a treble <qex>mort</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The skin of a sheep or lamb that has died of
disease.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mort cloth</b></col>, <cd>the pall spread over a coffin;
black cloth indicative or mourning; funeral hangings.</cd>
<au>Carlyle.</au> -- <col><b>Mort stone</b></col>, <cd>a large stone by
the wayside on which the bearers rest a coffin.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>
<au>H. Taylor.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mort</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mort
<hw>Mort</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mort</ets>
dummy, lit., dead.]</ety> <def>A variety of dummy whist for three
players; also, the exposed or dummy hand in this game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortal</ent>⟦br⟧
